  "Idea": "This research introduces Causal Code Reasoner (CCR), a novel paradigm for deep learning-based bug localization that unifies behaviorally-informed data augmentation with in-model causal reasoning to mitigate spurious correlations and enhance fault detection accuracy. While prior approaches such as BIDAFI improve data quality via realistic fault injection, they do not address how models themselves may exploit non-causal, dataset-specific patterns (e.g., frequent variable names near bugs, comment styles, or logging calls) that degrade generalization. CCR addresses this by embedding a dual-stage causal learning mechanism: (1) a Counterfactual Program Augmenter (CPA) that generates semantically valid, behaviorally divergent code variants using dynamic execution traces and causal dependency graphs (inspired by BIDAFI and ACAMDA), and (2) a Causal Intervention Network (CIN) integrated within the DLBL model that performs real-time counterfactual analysis during training to identify which code elements have a direct causal effect on prediction outcomes. Specifically, CPA constructs a Structural Causal Model (SCM) of each function using execution traces and static analysis, then applies targeted interventions (e.g., changing loop bounds, altering conditional branches) to generate minimal-deviation faulty versions. Each augmented sample is paired with a 'causal mask' indicating the intervened node(s). During training, the CIN uses these masks to compute the Expected Causal Effect (ECE) of each token by comparing predictions on factual and counterfactual inputs, effectively down-weighting features that change prediction without a true causal link. This process mimics human debugging intuition—focusing on changes that *explain* behavioral deviations rather than mere textual proximity. Furthermore, CCR incorporates an attention regularization term that aligns model attention weights with high-ECE regions, improving interpretability and reducing reliance on misguiding terms (e.g., 'FIXME' comments not associated with actual faults). We hypothesize that CCR will significantly outperform existing DLBL models in cross-project settings and rare bug type detection, where spurious correlations are most damaging. The broader impact includes advancing neuro-symbolic AI in software engineering by formalizing causal reasoning as a core component of model architecture—not just data preprocessing—paving the way for self-explaining, robust, and trustworthy AI-assisted debugging tools.",
