{
  "Idea": "This research proposes a novel framework called Behaviorally-Informed Data Augmentation for Realistic Fault Injection (BIDAFI), designed to enhance the accuracy and robustness of deep learning-based bug localization systems through semantically and behaviorally realistic synthetic fault generation. The core limitation in current DLBL models is their reliance on sparse, naturally occurring bug datasets, which often underrepresent rare but impactful fault types (e.g., off-by-one errors, incorrect loop conditions, null dereferences). Traditional data augmentation techniques—such as random token masking or syntactic rewriting—fail to preserve the causal structure of program execution, leading to unrealistic or functionally invalid code variants that degrade model performance. BIDAFI addresses this by integrating three key components: (1) dynamic execution tracing to capture program behavior under correct inputs, (2) causal dependency modeling using structural equation models (SEMs) over variable states and control flow, and (3) guided counterfactual fault injection that modifies specific program elements while ensuring the resulting code diverges meaningfully in output yet remains syntactically valid and semantically coherent. For instance, given a correct function computing array sums, BIDAFI might generate a faulty version that incorrectly initializes the accumulator to 1 instead of 0—producing a consistent deviation traceable to a single causal node in the execution graph. These counterfactual faults are then used to augment training data for DLBL models, enabling them to learn discriminative features between correct and subtly incorrect implementations. Crucially, each augmented sample comes with an associated 'fault signature'—a vector of behavioral deviations (e.g., output differences, memory access anomalies)—which can be leveraged during model training as auxiliary supervision signals. We hypothesize that training on such behaviorally grounded data will significantly improve model sensitivity to real-world bugs, reduce false positives caused by textual noise, and increase interpretability by aligning model attention with actual fault propagation paths. The impact of this work lies in bridging the gap between symbolic program analysis and neural learning paradigms, offering a principled way to scale high-quality labeled data for software engineering AI tasks. Potential applications extend beyond bug localization to include automated repair, test case generation, and vulnerability detection.",
